<section xml:id="sec-multivariate-probability">
  <title>Multivariate probability</title>

  <objectives>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Compute probabilities and expectations for jointly distributed variables using double integrals.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Obtain marginal densities by integrating out one variable from the joint distribution.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Approximate probabilities numerically with Monte Carlo methods when regions or densities are complex.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </objectives>
  
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Introduction goes here.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <p>
        Joint density function of <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m>:
        <me>
          \Prob ((X,Y)\in D)=\iint_{D} f(x,y)\dd{A}
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Expected values:
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\mu_X \amp = \iint_{D} xf(x,y)\dd{A}</mrow>
        <mrow>\mu_Y \amp = \iint_{D} yf(x,y)\dd{A}</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>
        These are just the center of mass again!
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Marginal probability density functions:
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>f_X(x) \amp = \int_{c}^{d} f(x,y)\dd{y}</mrow>
        <mrow>f_Y(y) \amp = \int_{a}^{b} f(x,y)\dd{x}</mrow>
      </md>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Could do Monte Carlo integration! Would be good practice still for setting up regions!
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
</section>
